WAYFARER PLATFORM
PRODUCT BIBLE
Feature ID: F-6.7.4 — Budget Intelligence (Category-Level Spend Model)
Version 2.0  ·  April 2026  ·  Binding Doctrine
1. Why This Feature Exists
Most travel tools ask: “What’s your budget?” and offer three buckets: budget, mid-range, luxury. That’s not how real people think about money when traveling.
Real travelers think: “I’ll pay $180 a night max for a hotel, but I’ll splurge on two special nights. I want to eat well but I’m not doing Michelin every night. I’d rather take a train than fly if it’s under 5 hours. And for this specific trip, I’m willing to stretch a bit because it’s my anniversary.”
Budget Intelligence stores those exact preferences — not buckets. It stores numeric thresholds, conditional rules, and per-trip overrides. Then the platform uses them everywhere: Trip Spark uses them to estimate trip costs. The context engine uses them to warn when a destination exceeds the traveler’s comfort. The Stay Range Engine (when built) uses them to filter accommodations. Deep Scan uses them to inform financial commentary.
This is where Wayfarer beats Layla. Layla accepts “budget and style” as general inputs. Wayfarer stores “$185/night max, tax included, with 2 splurge nights at $240, prefer trains in Europe, daily food target $60.” That precision makes every downstream recommendation sharper.

Binds to: user_profiles.preferences JSONB (storage), Section 7.4 (voice capture), F-6.7.3 (Trip Spark estimates), context engine evaluate.ts (budget-aware nudges), per-trip unlock model (conversion moment), Stay Range Engine F-6.7.6 (when built).
2. The Traveler’s Story
Story 1: Setting preferences
Marcus opens Account → Budget Preferences. He sees labeled input fields with clear helper text. He sets: max $180/night for hotels (tax included), splurge ceiling $250 (for 2 nights per trip), daily food target $65, daily activity budget $40, max one-way flight $600, prefers trains in Europe, travels as a couple, mostly international.
He taps Save. The platform stores this in user_profiles.preferences.budget_intelligence. From now on, every relevant surface has access to these numbers.
Story 2: Voice capture
During trip planning, Marcus says: “I don’t want to spend more than $200 a night on this trip.” The voice parse detects a budget signal. The platform asks: “Should I remember $200/night for future trips, or just this one?” Marcus says “Just this trip.” The value is stored in trips.metadata.budget_override.lodging_per_night_cap = 200.
Story 3: Context engine nudge
Marcus is building a Tokyo trip. His profile budget has lodging_per_night_cap = $180. The context engine knows Tokyo hotel averages exceed $200/night in cherry blossom season. During the pre_trip state, the RightNowPanel shows: “Your lodging target may be tight for Tokyo in April. Consider Osaka as a base for day trips, or adjust your budget for this trip.”
Story 4: Trip Spark integration
When Trip Spark offers to build a trip from saved Chile items, it includes: “Based on your preferences, a 7-day Chile trip is estimated at $1,600–$2,100. Atacama lodging fits your budget. Santiago is slightly over in peak season.”
3. Data Model
3.1 Storage Location
Budget Intelligence does NOT create a new table. It stores data in user_profiles.preferences (existing JSONB field) under the key budget_intelligence. Per-trip overrides go in trips.metadata.budget_override (existing JSONB field). No new migration needed for the base schema — JSONB is extensible.
3.2 Budget Intelligence Schema
Field	Type	Description
lodging_per_night_cap	number | null	Hard maximum per night, tax included. NULL = no cap set. This is the number the traveler never wants to exceed on a regular night.
lodging_splurge_ceiling	number | null	Maximum for a special-occasion night. NULL = same as cap. “I’ll go to $250 for an anniversary dinner hotel.”
lodging_splurge_frequency	number | null	How many splurge nights per trip. Integer 1–5. “2 special nights max.”
food_daily_comfort	number | null	Target daily food spend across all meals. “$65 a day for food.”
activity_daily_comfort	number | null	Target daily activity/experience spend. “$40 a day for things to do.”
flight_pain_threshold	number | null	Maximum acceptable one-way flight cost. “I won’t pay more than $600 for a flight.”
train_vs_flight_bias	string | null	prefer_train | prefer_flight | cost_driven | time_driven | no_preference. “I’d rather take a train in Europe.”
total_daily_target	number | null	Overall daily spend target across all categories. “I want to stay around $250/day total.”
travel_mode	string | null	solo | couple | family | group. Affects multipliers for estimates.
domestic_vs_international	string | null	domestic | international | both. Traveler may have different comfort levels.
currency	string	ISO 4217 currency code for display. Default ‘USD’.
last_updated	string (ISO timestamp)	When budget preferences were last modified.
3.3 Per-Trip Override
Any field from the budget schema can be overridden at the trip level. Stored in trips.metadata.budget_override as a partial BudgetIntelligence object. Trip-level values take precedence over profile-level values when present.
Example: profile has lodging_per_night_cap = 180, but trips.metadata.budget_override.lodging_per_night_cap = 200 for the anniversary trip. The system uses 200 for that trip.
3.4 Security Classification
T2 (Sensitive). Financial preference data is personal. Budget numbers reveal spending capacity and lifestyle. Field-level encryption on lodging_per_night_cap and flight_pain_threshold (the most revealing values). RLS: user_profiles is already account-scoped. No budget data in logs, events, or error messages.
